"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.5.3.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.5.3.1</span> Jinglet, bell</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">פַּעֲמֹן</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(pa‘amon)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:33\">EXO 28:33</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:34\">EXO 28:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:34\">EXO 28:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:25\">EXO 39:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:25\">EXO 39:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:26\">EXO 39:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:26\">EXO 39:26</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κώδων</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kōdōn)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir45:9\">SIR 45:9</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0460_bell.jpg\" alt=\"Bells and jinglets on the high priest&#x27;s garments\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Bells and jinglets on the high priest&#x27;s garments (© Ben P L, CC BY 2.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Jinglets were small platelets of metal. Their exact size and shape are not known. They were sewn to the hem of the High Priest’s robe (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.5.3 Robe&lt;REALIA:4.5.3&gt;</a>). As he walked or moved, they knocked together making a jingling or tinkling sound.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Bells as we know them today, with a bell shape containing a ringing clapper, were not known at the time of Exodus and are probably not intended. Nevertheless, almost all the modern translations consulted render the Hebrew word <em>pa‘amon</em> as “bells” (for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>). Where a word for jingling platelets exists and is commonly understood, it should be used. Otherwise translators may use “bells,” since they have the same function and are not very different in form. Where “bells” are not known, it will be necessary to find some sort of ornamentation, made of pieces of metal (perhaps coins) or even shells, which makes a sound when the clothing is moved.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
